    {
      "id": "RecentPost166516",
      "post_content": "I still believe that Shock was right, Cancel was wrong, and reprinting Lightning Bolt while continuing to not print Counterspell is double-super-deluxe wrong. Proactive spells should be weaker than reactive ones, because reactive ones don't inherently do anything. If you have a super-strong counterspell, but your opponent never actually casts a spell, you're just sitting there accomplishing nothing, which means all your opponent has to do is wait until your patience gives out and you squander your resources and give him an opening. Strong counterspells create an interesting tension in gameplay as you need to balance counteroffense with the need to actually accomplish anything. Strong burn, by converse, just lets you randomly win games in a lame way by bolting the opponent for 3 right when he stabilizes, making him feel like he wasted his effort shuffling. Sure, my philosophy can lead to games taking forever, but I think that's preferable to ten-minute blowouts which are crushing f... [(see all)](javascript:void(0);)",
      "posted_by": "willpell",
      "html": "<div class=\"post oddItem\" id=\"RecentPost166516\">\n<span id=\"ctl00_ctl00_ctl00_MainContent_SubContent_SubContent_recentPosts_postsRepeater_ctl05_post\">I still believe that Shock was right, Cancel was wrong, and reprinting Lightning Bolt while continuing to not print Counterspell is double-super-deluxe wrong.  Proactive spells should be weaker than reactive ones, because reactive ones don't inherently do anything.  If you have a super-strong counterspell, but your opponent never actually casts a spell, you're just sitting there accomplishing nothing, which means all your opponent has to do is wait until your patience gives out and you squander your resources and give him an opening.  Strong counterspells create an interesting tension in gameplay as you need to balance counteroffense with the need to actually accomplish anything.  Strong burn, by converse, just lets you randomly win games in a lame way by bolting the opponent for 3 right when he stabilizes, making him feel like he wasted his effort shuffling.  Sure, my philosophy can lead to games taking forever, but I think that's preferable to ten-minute blowouts which are crushing f... <a href=\"javascript:void(0);\" onclick=\"ExpandPost(event, this, 166516)\">(see all)</a></span>\n<div class=\"postDetails\" id=\"ctl00_ctl00_ctl00_MainContent_SubContent_SubContent_recentPosts_postsRepeater_ctl05_postDetails\" style=\"padding-top: 5px;\">\n<div class=\"reportAbuse\">\n<a href=\"http://wizards.custhelp.com/cgi-bin/wizards.cfg/php/enduser/std_adp.php?p_faqid=1208\" id=\"ctl00_ctl00_ctl00_MainContent_SubContent_SubContent_recentPosts_postsRepeater_ctl05_reportAbuseLink\">\r\n                                    Report Abuse</a>\u00a0\u00a0\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\n<div class=\"postedBy\">\r\n                                Posted By: <a class=\"postedByLink\" href=\"javascript:void(0);\" id=\"PostedBy1041\">willpell</a>\r\n                            